		<p>This whole article is bogus. Back in 2006 I was charged with a DUID (Driving under the influence of drugs) not because I was impaired, but because my vehicle smelled like marijuana. I had no way to fight the charge, even though I had not been smoking, and the smell was a result of a hot box from the day before. I preformed a roadside test at the request of the officer, and passed. But none of that mattered to the police. If they have something that can test saliva to determine whether someone has recently been smoking, that still doesn&#8217;t address the issue of actual impairment. It seems that it is always going to be up to the discretion of the police to decide when they feel someone is too impaired to drive. Which for marijuana users is a very unfortunate reality, because marijuana will get lumped together with alcohol and other severely impairing substances, when we all know that even smoking six joints back to back, is less impairing than having six alcoholic drinks. </p>
		
		
